Voting equipment being used such as indelible ink for marking voters' fingers to ensure they vote only once and transparent ballot boxes ``are all recognised as ensuring fair and honest elections,'' the Kyrgyz leader said after casting his vote in the capital Bishkek. The parliamentary elections, which are a stepping stone to presidential elections on October 30, have been surrounded by controversy, with protests in several parts of this mountainous country in the days leading up to the vote. 